"{\"uid\": \"express.co.uk-sport-tennis-1931704-Olympics-2024-Novak-Djokovic-Matthew-Ebden-John-Peers\", \"text\": \"  A lot can happen in one week, as Australia's Matthew Ebden learned at the Olympics. The doubles world No. 3 got into the singles draw as an alternate following withdrawals and was thrashed by Novak Djokovic 6-0 6-1.  Immediately after the match, Ebdenannounced that he had officially retired from singles tennisand turned his attention to the men's doubles draw with John Peers.  Seven days later, the Aussies won an Olympic gold medal, coming from a set and break down to beat Austin Krajicek and Rajeev Ram of the USA in a match tiebreak 6-7(6) 7-6(1) [10-8].  Ebden looked lost on the court when he came out to face top seed Djokovic in singles last Saturday. It took 46 minutes for him to win his first and only game of the match after training 0-6 0-4. Early in the second set,he even resorted to trying to quit the match, jokingly handing his racket to a spectator so he could sub out.  The 36-year-old had not played a singles match in almost two years, since an outing in the qualifying rounds of the ATP 250 event in Winston-Salem. And he officially quit the game afterwards. \\\"Safe to say I am officially retired from singles after that,\\\" he wrote onInstagram.  After turning his attention back to his real specialism, doubles, he managed to win his first gold medal alongside compatriot and neighbour Peers. After securing the win, Ebden confessed that his loss to Djokovic was on his mind. \\\" Honestly, yes. I think last night, I did think of it a bit,\\\" he said.  Just in:Olympic gold medallist 'really sad' after 'destroying friendship' with victory    Our community members are treated to special offers, promotions, and adverts from us and our partners. You can check out at any time. Read ourPrivacy Policy  The doubles star was even pre-planning a celebratory social media post. \\\"I was actually dreaming of an Instagram post like how it started, how it's going. I was thinking of my score [seven] days ago, winning one game, and then I was thinking swipe right and there is a gold medal photo. Maybe I will have to make that post at some point,\\\" he laughed.  Ebden also revealed that he defied orders from Australia's tennis captain for the Olympics, Lleyton Hewitt, to get the chance to officially see off his singles career. He continued: \\\"I did come off that singles match fully focused on the doubles. Literally when I got the call up to play [singles], Lleyton was like, 'No do not play, you save your body, make sure do not get injured. You are not here for that, I want a medal in the doubles or the mixed, whatever.'  \\\"And I said, 'Okay, I will play but I promise I will not get injured.' So my main goal that match was just not to get injured and I did that, had a hit, had some fun. Got to officially retire from singles which was nice. My wife was liking that, I never officially played my last official retirement singles match and she thought I deserved a nice little match like that. So that was a nice little miracle that happened to say goodbye to my singles career.\\\"  Do not miss:Djokovic sends threat to Alcaraz as Serb seeks revenge for Wimbledon  Do not miss:Tennis star defaulted and booed after throwing racket and swearing at fan  Do not miss:Djokovic defies injury to reach first Olympics final and set Alcaraz rematch  We use your sign-up to provide content in ways you have consented to and to improve our understanding of you. This may include adverts from us and 3rd parties based on our understanding. You can unsubscribe at any time. Read ourPrivacy Policy    His focus on the doubles paid off, and Ebden and Peers walked away with their first gold medal. Peers had previously won bronze in the mixed doubles with Ash Barty in Tokyo. Ebden added: \\\"It's more than a dream, I did not even dream of winning a gold medal growing up or whatever. The last few years, had great success on the doubles court and it gave me a lot of belief and confidence coming in here.  \\\"We spoke a few months ago about our partnership, our best chance to win and he said, what are you looking for? I said looking for our best chance to win. We believed in ourselves, we started a few months ago already thinking and preparing about this. Even all week here, all the tough matches so I am super happy to get the reward because you do not always get the reward for all of your hard work, but when you do it's pretty sweet.\\\"  SEARCH  CONNECT WITH US  TODAY'S PAPER  See today's front and back pages, download the newspaper, order back issues and use the historic Daily Express newspaper archive.  EXPRESS.CO.UK  Daily Express uses notifications to keep you updated\"}"